Linked list
Defination :-A linked list is a linear data structure that consists of a sequence of elements called nodes. 
            - where each node points to the next node by means of a pointer.
            - Each node contains data and a reference (or link) to the next node in the sequence. 
            - Unlike arrays, linked lists do not store elements in contiguous memory locations. 
            - The elements in a linked list are not stored in contiguous memory locations, 
            - which means that the elements can be scattered throughout the memory.
            - this allows linked lists to be more flexible than arrays, as they can grow and shrink in size dynamically.

